\end_inset

 is onto.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
False.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be the identity function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g(f(x))=g(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

 is not onto.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is onto and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is 1-to-1, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

 is 1-to-1.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
False.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(g\circ f)(-1)=g(1)=1=g(1)=(g\circ f)(1).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are 1-to-1, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

